===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[prepare]] (usually a [[beverage]]) by [[steep]]ing and [[mingle|mingling]]; to [[concoct]].
#* [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]]
#*: Go, '''brew''' me a pottle of sack finely.
# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[foment]] or prepare, as by brewing; to [[contrive]]; to [[plot]]; to hatch.
#* [[w:John Milton|John Milton]]
#*: Hence with thy '''brewed''' enchantments, foul deceiver!
# {{label|en|intransitive}} To [[attend]] to the business, or go through the processes, of brewing or making beer.
#* [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]]
#*: I wash, wring, '''brew''', bake, scour.
# {{label|en|intransitive}} To be in a state of preparation; to be [[mix]]ing, forming, or [[gather]]ing.
#* [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]]
#*: There is some ill a-'''brewing''' towards my rest.
#* {{quote-journal|date=January 11, 2011
|author=Jonathan Stevenson
|title=West Ham 2 - 1 Birmingham
|work=BBC
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/9354485.stm
|page=
|passage=Grant may have considered that only a performance of the very highest quality could keep him in a job - and the way his players started the game gave the 55-year-old shelter from the storm that was '''brewing'''.}}
